item.description:
arXiv:2606.29292v3 Announce Type: replace 
Abstract: Fix a chaos order $m\ge1$. Let $(M,g)$ be a smooth closed Riemannian surface, let $X_N$ be a smooth spectral truncation of the massive Gaussian free field, and set $\Phi_{m,N}=\mathopen{:}X_N^m\mathclose{:}$. For dyadic spectral blocks and $2\le r<\infty$, we prove \[
  \|\Lambda_g^{-a}\Delta_LM_{\Phi_{m,N}}\Delta_Q\Lambda_g^{-b}
  \|_{L^p(\Omega;\mathfrak S_r)}
  \lesssim
  (p+r)^{m/2}\bigl(\log(e+\max\{L,Q\})\bigr)^{m/2}
  \min\{L,Q\}^{2/r}L^{-a}Q^{-b}, \] uniformly in the ultraviolet cutoff. Although the block estimate is established for $2\le r<\infty$, smoothing coherence and Schatten H\"older yield the global result for every $1\le r<\infty$: if $a,b>0$ and $a+b>2/r$, the sandwiched multipliers converge in $L^p(\Omega;\mathfrak S_r)$ and almost surely along dyadic cutoffs. The limit is independent of the smooth ultraviolet profile and the dyadic spectral resolution, and its matrix coefficients represent the cutoff-independent Wick distribution. The constant Gaussian mode shows that $a+b>2/r$ is necessary for every $1\le r<\infty$.
  The probabilistic input is a dimension-free finite-Schatten estimate for operator-valued Gaussian chaoses controlled by all oriented flattenings: \[
  \|\mathcal T_K^{(m)}\|_{L^p(\Omega;\mathfrak S_r)}
  \le C_m(p+r)^{m/2}
  \max_{S\subset[m]}\|\mathcal F_S(K)\|_{\mathfrak S_r}. \] For fixed $m$, the joint dependence on $p$ and $r$ is optimal. A Gaussian regression identity transfers the estimate to same-field Wick chaos with factor $m^{m/2}$, the optimal universal constant in increasing convex order. In the surface application, a cut-dependent factorization through $L^2(M)$ and Schatten interpolation yield the gain $\min\{L,Q\}^{2/r}$ required for the global summation.
